# CLAUDE.md TEMPLATE (project-specific — customize before use)

## 🔒 SECURITY RULES — NON-OVERRIDABLE
1) Token Protection (`token_do_not_commit/`)
   - NEVER read, print, echo, or expose contents of files in `token_do_not_commit/`.
   - NEVER include token values in output, logs, commit messages, or responses.
   - NEVER suggest committing or uploading files from `token_do_not_commit/`.
   - USE tokens only via environment variables, e.g., `source token_do_not_commit/.bws-token`.
   - Warn the user and refuse if an operation would expose these tokens.
2) Maximum Security Protocol
   - Treat everything in `token_do_not_commit/` as root-level secrets.
   - Verify `.gitignore` contains `token_do_not_commit/` before any git operations.
3) General secret hygiene
   - Do not commit or display passwords, API keys, personal emails, internal IPs, or service credentials.
   - Use vaults (e.g., BWS) and environment variables; use placeholders in docs/examples.

## ⚠️ CRITICAL SECURITY NOTICE
- Never commit or expose sensitive items; prefer placeholders and config templates.
- Security scan status: ensure hardcoded credentials are removed or vaulted before committing.

## PROJECT PLAN INTEGRATION
- Read `PROJECT_PLAN.md` at session start to understand context, architecture, priorities.
- In plan mode: refine the existing plan; on exit, update `PROJECT_PLAN.md` with new decisions.
- Treat `PROJECT_PLAN.md` as the single source of truth for planning artifacts.

## CONTEXT HANDLING
- Summaries are stored in `sessions/logs/`; optional compact copies in `.claude/context/`.
- No automatic preload into Claude Code. Only load past summaries when explicitly requested.
- If loading manually, prefer the newest items first to conserve tokens.

## CODING PRINCIPLES
- KISS: prefer the simplest viable solution.
- DRY: avoid duplication; reuse abstractions.
- SOLID: respect single responsibility and extension over modification.
- YAGNI: implement only what is needed now.
- Security First: never commit credentials; use vault-managed secrets.

## DOCUMENTATION STANDARDS
- Keep `CLAUDE.md` focused on stable architecture and procedures.
- Do NOT include transient status, bug lists, or “currently broken” notes.
- Record factual specifications: what components do, how they interact, intended behaviors.

## WORKFLOW GUIDELINES (Claude Code)
- Plan before edits: generate/agree a plan, then execute against it.
- Keep skills ON-DEMAND to conserve context. Recommended set available:
  - TDD, playwright regression, deploy-production, context-compaction,
    spec-driven dev, code-review/refactor, error-fix, docs writer.
- Use worktrees/branches per feature when possible; isolate changes.
- Require verification (tests/linters) before marking tasks complete when applicable.

